            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the ponderal index?</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>ponderal index (PI)</strong>, also known as the
                <strong>corpulence index</strong> or
                <strong>Rohrer index</strong>, is an anthropometric measure that
                relates <strong>body weight</strong> to
                <strong>height cubed</strong>. It is designed to reflect how
                “compact” or “slender” a body is, taking into account that body
                <em>volume</em> scales roughly with the cube of height.
              </p>
              <p>
                PI is widely used in <strong>neonatology</strong> and
                <strong>pediatrics</strong> to assess growth and proportionality
                in newborns and children, and it can also be calculated in
                adults as an alternative to BMI.
              </p>

              <h2>Ponderal index formula</h2>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Metric units</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{PI} = \dfrac{\text{weight (kg)}}{\text{height (m)}^3}
                  \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3 font-semibold mb-2">
                  Imperial units (pounds, inches)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{PI} = 12 \times \dfrac{\text{weight
                  (lb)}}{\text{height (in)}^3} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
                  The factor 12 comes from converting pounds to kilograms and
                  inches to meters so that the result is still expressed in
                  kg/m³.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example calculation (adult)</h3>
              <p>Suppose an adult weighs 70 kg and is 1.75 m tall.</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Convert height to meters if needed: 175 cm = 1.75 m.</li>
                <li>
                  Cube the height: \( 1.75^3 \approx 5.36 \,\text{m}^3 \).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply the formula: \( \text{PI} = 70 / 5.36 \approx 13.1
                  \,\text{kg/m}^3 \).
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                A PI around 13 kg/m³ is typical for a healthy adult, but there
                are no universally agreed adult cut-offs like there are for BMI.
              </p>

              <h2>How to interpret ponderal index</h2>
              <p>
                Interpretation depends on <strong>age</strong> and
                <strong>population</strong>. This calculator provides a
                <em>rough guide</em> only and is not a diagnostic tool.
              </p>

              <h3>Adults (approximate guide)</h3>
              <p>
                For adults, PI is less standardized than BMI, but the following
                ranges are often cited in the literature:
              </p>
              <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      PI (kg/m³)
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Interpretation (approximate)
                    </th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">&lt; 11</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Low corpulence / possibly underweight
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">11 – 15</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Typical range for many adults
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">&gt; 15</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Higher corpulence / possibly overweight
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Use these values cautiously; BMI and waist measurements are
                better validated for adult risk assessment.
              </p>

              <h3>Newborns and infants</h3>
              <p>
                In neonatology, PI is commonly used to distinguish between
                <strong>proportionate</strong> and
                <strong>disproportionate</strong> growth restriction. Typical
                values for <strong>term newborns</strong> are often in the
                range:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>PI &lt; 23 kg/m³</strong> – may suggest wasting or
                  intrauterine growth restriction (IUGR).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>PI 23–26 kg/m³</strong> – often considered typical for
                  term newborns.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>PI &gt; 26 kg/m³</strong> – may indicate relatively
                  high mass for length (e.g., macrosomia or edema).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Exact thresholds vary by gestational age, sex, and reference
                charts. Always interpret in conjunction with clinical
                assessment.
              </p>

              <h2>Ponderal index vs BMI</h2>
              <p>
                Both PI and BMI are <strong>indices of body size</strong>, but
                they scale differently with height:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>BMI</strong>: \( \text{BMI} =
                  \dfrac{\text{weight}}{\text{height}^2} \) (kg/m²)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>PI</strong>: \( \text{PI} =
                  \dfrac{\text{weight}}{\text{height}^3} \) (kg/m³)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because body <em>volume</em> scales with height³, PI may be less
                biased by height, especially in very short or very tall
                individuals and in newborns. BMI, however, has extensive
                epidemiological data and is standard in adult practice.
              </p>
              <p>
                In adolescents, some research suggests that
                <strong>tri-ponderal mass index (TMI)</strong>, which is
                essentially the same form as PI (weight/height³), may track body
                fat better than BMI during growth spurts. This calculator uses
                the classic PI formulation; for clinical decisions, follow local
                guidelines.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and clinical use</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  PI is a <strong>screening tool</strong>, not a diagnosis.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not distinguish between <strong>fat mass</strong> and
                  <strong>lean mass</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Interpretation should consider
                  <strong>age, sex, ethnicity, gestational age</strong> (for
                  newborns), and clinical context.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For adults, BMI, waist circumference, and body composition
                  measures are usually preferred.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Always consult a qualified health professional for
                interpretation of anthropometric indices and for any concerns
                about growth, nutrition, or body weight.
              </p>
            </section>
